---
import CalculatorLayout from '../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import RothConversionCalculator from '../../components/calculators/RothConversionCalculator';
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title="Roth Conversion Calculator for Trump Accounts"
  description="Model the pro rata rule, standard deduction chunking, and multi-year Roth conversion strategy. See how much tax you'll owe — and how much you'll save."
  calculatorName="Roth Conversion Calculator"
  slug="roth-conversion"
  abstract="Calculate the optimal Roth IRA conversion strategy for a Trump Account that converts to a traditional IRA at age 18. Models the pro rata rule for nondeductible basis, standard deduction sheltering, multi-year conversion chunking, and lifetime Roth growth projections."
>
  <section class="mb-8">
    <h2 class="mb-3 text-xl font-bold text-white">Why This Calculator Matters</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
      When your child's Trump Account becomes a traditional IRA at age 18, you have a once-in-a-lifetime
      opportunity: convert to a Roth IRA while they're in the <strong class="text-white">lowest tax bracket of their life</strong>.
      Because Trump Account contributions are after-tax (nondeductible), only the growth portion is taxed on
      conversion — the pro rata rule works in your favor.
    </p>
    <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3 mb-6">
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-surface-600 bg-surface-800 p-3 text-center">
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Step 1</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium text-white mt-1">Trump Account</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Ages 0–17</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-surface-600 bg-surface-800 p-3 text-center">
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Step 2</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium text-white mt-1">Traditional IRA</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Converts at 18</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-gold-400/30 bg-gold-400/5 p-3 text-center">
        <p class="text-xs text-gold-400">Step 3</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-bold text-gold-400 mt-1">Roth IRA</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Convert strategically</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div id="calculator">
    <RothConversionCalculator client:visible />
  </div>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="mb-3 text-xl font-bold text-white">How the Pro Rata Rule Works</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-sm text-gray-400">
      <p>
        Trump Account contributions are made with <strong class="text-white">after-tax dollars</strong> — you don't get a tax deduction.
        This creates <strong class="text-white">nondeductible basis</strong> in the account. When you convert to a Roth IRA,
        the IRS uses the pro rata rule to determine how much of each converted dollar is taxable:
      </p>
      <ul class="text-gray-300">
        <li><strong class="text-white">Basis percentage</strong> = Total contributions ÷ Account balance</li>
        <li><strong class="text-white">Taxable percentage</strong> = 1 − Basis percentage</li>
        <li>Each dollar converted = (basis %) tax-free + (taxable %) ordinary income</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong class="text-white">Example:</strong> If you contributed $60,000 and the account grew to $100,000,
        your basis is 60%. For every $1 you convert, $0.60 is tax-free and $0.40 is taxable.
        The IRS does not let you cherry-pick which dollars to convert — it must be proportional.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2 class="mb-3 text-xl font-bold text-white">The Standard Deduction Chunking Strategy</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-sm text-gray-400">
      <p>
        The key to a <strong class="text-white">zero-tax conversion</strong> is keeping the taxable portion of each
        year's conversion under the standard deduction. If your child has no other income, they can convert
        enough each year so the taxable portion equals the standard deduction — and owe <strong class="text-white">$0 in federal tax</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For larger accounts, spread the conversion over 2–4 college years when income is low.
        Even if your child has a part-time job, they're likely in the 10% or 12% bracket — far lower
        than the 22%+ they'll pay later in their career.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2 class="mb-3 text-xl font-bold text-white">Related Resources</h2>
    <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <a href="/trump-account-roth-conversion-strategy" class="rounded-lg border border-surface-600 p-4 no-underline hover:border-gold-400/30 hover:bg-gold-400/5 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-white">Roth Conversion Strategy Guide</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">The complete pillar guide to converting Trump Accounts to Roth IRAs</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/blog/trump-account-to-roth-ira-zero-tax" class="rounded-lg border border-surface-600 p-4 no-underline hover:border-gold-400/30 hover:bg-gold-400/5 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-white">How $60K Becomes an $8.8M Roth IRA</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">The step-by-step breakdown with real numbers</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</CalculatorLayout>
